 Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1364–":"about 1364–Deceased","1364–Female":"1364–Deceased","1361–Male":"1361–Deceased","1392–Male":"1392–Deceased","1394–Female":"1394–Deceased","1400–1464":"1400–1464","1425–1464":"1425–1464","–Male":"Deceased","1313–Male":"1313–Deceased","about 1392":"about 1392","1425":"1425","1313":"1313","1400":"1400","1464":"1464","1364":"1364","about 1400":"about 1400","1394":"1394","1361":"1361","1392":"1392","about 1364":"about 1364","about 1394":"about 1394","of Tichborne, Hampshire, England":"Tichborne, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Hampshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mocking","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: relationship name ‘son of  <i>Mocke</i>’;  see  Mock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mock","meanings":["English (Devon): from the Middle English personal name <i>Moke</i>, theoretically in some instances a survival of Old English <i>Mocca</i>, but usually a shortened form of <i>Mocok</i>, a pet form of <i>Matthew</i>. See   Maycock   and   Moxon  .","German: variant of   Maag  .","German (also <b>Möck</b>): nickname for a thickset, unmannered man, from Middle High German <i>mocke</i> ‘lump’. Compare   Moeck  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Mocking was born about 1364, in Hampshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of John Mocking. She married John Tichborne about 1400, in Tichborne, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1364–":"umbes 1364–Surnud","1364–Female":"1364–Surnud","1361–Male":"1361–Surnud","1392–Male":"1392–Surnud","1394–Female":"1394–Surnud","1400–1464":"1400–1464","1425–1464":"1425–1464","–Male":"Surnud","1313–Male":"1313–Surnud","about 1392":"umbes 1392","1425":"1425","1313":"1313","1400":"1400","1464":"1464","1364":"1364","about 1400":"umbes 1400","1394":"1394","1361":"1361","1392":"1392","about 1364":"umbes 1364","about 1394":"umbes 1394","of Tichborne, Hampshire, England":"Tichborne, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hampshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1364–":"noin 1364–Kuollut","1364–Female":"1364–Kuollut","1361–Male":"1361–Kuollut","1392–Male":"1392–Kuollut","1394–Female":"1394–Kuollut","1400–1464":"1400–1464","1425–1464":"1425–1464","–Male":"Kuollut","1313–Male":"1313–Kuollut","about 1392":"noin 1392","1425":"1425","1313":"1313","1